<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Professor Colin Talbot</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Professor Colin Talbot</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Professor of Government, University of Manchester (FTF 07)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">SPENDING REVIEWS, BUDGETS AND</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> FIXED-</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">TERM PARLIAMENTS</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">This submission will address one specific aspect of the Inquiry</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> terms of reference</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“The Spending Review announced in June 2013 covers the 2015/16 financial year only. What discussions can take place in the final year of the current Parliament to prepare</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> for the next Spending Review?</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What scope is there for future Spending Reviews to more closely mirror the term of a Parliament?”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The submission will widen the scope slightly of this question, to include how Spending Reviews and the whole Finance and Suppl</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">y system might be impacted by the changes introduced by the FTP Act.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">SPENDING REVIEWS AND BUDGETS</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">It is </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">very </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">important to be clear about the status of Spending Reviews. They are simply ‘statements of intent’ by the government, in effect </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">they have</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> the sam</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">e status as a White Paper. They are not authorised by Parliament and, apart from the short-lived Fiscal Responsibility Act of Feb 2010</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">, Spending Reviews had no legal basis or force.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Each SR only attains real force when it is implemented through subsequen</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">t annual Budgets</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. One problematic issue has been that Budgets – and subsequent Supply motions – do not always follow what was set out in the Spending Review for the relevant year. Moreover Governments do not make it clear when they are deviating from the p</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">lan set out in the preceding Spending Review.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">In the latter years of the Labour government, and under the Coalition, this situation has become even more complicated as governments have increasingly used the Pre Budget Report (or ‘Autumn Statement’) to mak</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">e changes to both tax and spending policies</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">, increasingly looking like a mini-budget</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">As </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Alistair Darling, Chancellor of the Exchequer from 2007 to 2010, remarks that “during my time as Chancellor I had to deliver what were in effect six Budgets”</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">SPENDING REVIEWS – THE STORY SO FAR</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">On its election in 1997 the New Labour Government announced it was introducing multi-year ‘Spending Reviews’, the first of which would be published </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">in the following year</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> (1998)</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. These would provide the public spending </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">framework for a 3-year period ahead.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The aims of this innovation were several:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">To provide increased stability to the public finances by specifying the public spending envelop</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> for three years in advance;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">To allow individual Ministries to plan more strat</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">egically over the medium-term and end the scourge of “annualarity”</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">To allow for greater ‘end-year flexibilities’ </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">moving a (limited and agreed) amount of spending between years; etc.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The idea of Governments adopting a medium-term expenditure framework </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">is not </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">especially </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">new –</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> the World Bank and IMF had</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> been promoting this idea to developing countries for many years before the UK decided to experiment with </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">it. However few OECD countries had adopted such a reform at the time and there was therefore a great</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> deal of interest in the British experiment.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">As promised, Labour duly published its first “Comprehensive Spending Review”</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> in J</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">uly 1998, setting out departmental budgets for the next three fiscal years (1999-2000 to 2001-02).</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> Since then there have been si</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">x further Spending Reviews, four under Labour and two under the Coalition. These are set out in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Figure </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_Ref250906930"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold">Figure </span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold">1</span></a><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold"> The History of Spending </span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold">Reviews</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:106.45pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Spending review – </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">year</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> of publication</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:106.45pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Period covered (fiscal years</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">*</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">)</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:106.45pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Number of years - proposed</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:106.45pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Number of years - actual</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:106.45pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">1998</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:106.45pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">1999-2001</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:106.45pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">3</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-